first county wildlife trust; while Blickling Hall was the first property to be accepted by the National Trust under its Country House Scheme. By the 1970s traditional marsheswere seen as particularly under threat and it was proposals to drain part of the Broadland marshes that led to the introduction of conservation schemes which have transformed much of British agriculture. In this engaging book, the author traces the history of the conservation movement and the people who were involved, including the Norfolk botanist and founder of the Linnean Society, Sir James Smith. In particular, she shows the influence of changingsocial attitudes and priorities upon the movement and ideas of heritage. Susanna Wade Martins is an honorary fellow of the School of History at the University of East Anglia; her previous publications include Coke ofNorfolk: A Biography and The Countryside of East Anglia (with Tom Williamson).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConservation of natural resourcesxHistoryzEnglandzNorfolk. 0aCultural propertyxProtectionxHistoryzEnglandzNorfolk. 0aGerman literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aGerman literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aHistoric preservationxHistoryzEnglandzNorfolk. 4aBritish Local History. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBlickling Hall.  aBritish Agriculture.  aConservation Movement.  aConservation Schemes.  aCultural Development.  aEnvironmental Conservation.  aEnvironmental History.  aEnvironmental Protection.  aHeritage.  aHistory.  aNorfolk Archaeological Trust.  aNorfolk Naturalist Trust.  aNorfolk.  aSocial Attitudes.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z9783111